3, 454)].\"},{\"summary\":\"Drawing legends and coded identifiers organize the plan set\",\"explanation\":\"The LEGEND entity and repeated coded labels such as W01, W02, W21, W22, W23, W25, W26, D01, D02, and G01/G02 show that the plan set relies heavily on standardized identifiers. The legend explicitly defines wall, window, door, and piping categories, allowing the drawings to be read consistently across architectural and HVAC sheets [Data: Entities (1549, 1550, 1552, 1553, 1554, +more); Relationships (2107, 2109, 2110, 2111, 2471, +more)].\\n\\nThis coding structure extends across elevation drawings, plan layouts, and thermal-performance documentation, making the community a tightly connected documentation ecosystem. The presence of repeated identifiers across multiple sheets suggests careful coordination among architectural, structural, and systems documentation [Data: Entities (1597, 471, 468, 469, 359, +more); Relationships (2233, 686, 678, 381, 394, +more)].\"},{\"summary\":\"Concrete and insulation materials dominate the envelope design\",\"explanation\":\"The building assemblies repeatedly reference concrete, cement mortar, gypsum board, plasterboard, wallpaper, and extruded insulation board as core construction materials. Concrete appears as a primary structural layer, while insulation and finish layers are used to build up wall and floor assemblies, indicating a conventional but performance-conscious residential envelope [Data: Entities (340, 339, 342, 343, 341, 372, +more); Relationships (372, 378, 422, 374, 379, +more)].\\n\\nThe way these materials are grouped in the tables shows that thermal resistance and transmittance are being engineered through layered assemblies. This reinforces that the community is centered on building physics and compliance documentation rather than on operational or business activities [Data: Relationships (407, 408, 409, 410, 453, +more)].\"},{\"summary\":\"Balcony, entryway, and living spaces are tied to performance detailing\",\"explanation\":\"The documentation does not limit performance analysis to exterior walls; it also ties in balcony, entryway, living room, and bedroom-related sections. BALCONY 2 appears in multiple wall-section and thermal-performance contexts, while ENTRYWAY and LIVING ROOM are linked to wall detail references such as W22, W23, W26, and W5 [Data: Entities (350, 347, 346, 401, 355, +more); Relationships (418, 402, 404, 377, 388, +more)].\\n\\nThis indicates that the project treats transitional and occupied interior spaces as part of the envelope-performance system. The result is a more complete building specification that connects occupant spaces to thermal and material performance requirements [Data: Entities (393, 404, 406, 534, 574); Relationships (466, 472, 2147, 2241)].\"},{\"summary\":\"HVAC and drainage legends show ancillary system documentation\",\"explanation\":\"Beyond the envelope, the plan set includes HVAC piping and drainage documentation, with legend entries for low-pressure gas pipe, high-pressure gas pipe, PVC pipe, and copper pipe. These records show that mechanical and plumbing systems are also cataloged in the same document ecosystem, though they are secondary to the envelope-performance focus [Data: Entities (1761, 1762, 1759, 1758, 568); Relationships (2474, 2475, 2472, 2471, 745)].\\n\\nThe inclusion of these system legends suggests a comprehensive project drawing package covering multiple disciplines. Even so, the strongest evidence of community cohesion remains the repeated linkage between the same codes, the legend, and the performance tables [Data: Entities (1549, 1597, 497); Relationships (2107, 2109, 2233, 603)].\"},{\"summary\":\"Test reports and standards references support performance claims\",\"explanation\":\"Several items are explicitly supported by test-report references or noted as attached test documentation, which adds evidentiary weight to the performance specifications. For example, the glazing performance item is link